<h2>
Introduction:</h2>
This lab examines and lists the local integer and floating point environments
with respect to limits on&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>csci</i>.
<h2>
Lab Assignment:</h2>

<ol>
<ol>
<li>
Create a new directory, <i>lab4</i>, and move to it.</li>

<li>
<i>run</i>: <b>cp</b> ~cs201400/lab4/writelimits.cpp mylimits.cpp</li>

<li>
<i>Edit </i>this file to include <u>all</u> of the information in Tables
E-1 and E-2 on pages 778 and 779 of our C++&nbsp;text.</li>

<li>
<i>Compile</i> (<tt>g++ -Wall mylimits.cpp -o mylimits</tt>)</li>

<li>
<i>Run</i></li>

<li>
<i>Debug </i>(if necessary)</li>

<li>
<i>Print</i>&nbsp; the output&nbsp; and your&nbsp; <u>source</u> file together
using <b>lpr -# 2</b> <i>outputfilename</i>.</li>

<li>
<i><u>Circle</u></i>&nbsp; by hand those limit values which differ from those in
our text.</li>

<li>
Hand in one printout.</li>

<li>
Retain one printout for your notes.</li>
</ol>
</ol>

<h4>
Editing Suggestions:</h4>

<li>
run <b>vim</b></li>

<li>
set the following flags:</li>

<blockquote>
<li>
":set cin sw=4"&nbsp; {this maintains indenting.&nbsp; See p. 206 of our Unix
text for details}</li>

<li>
":syntax enable" {provides automatic syntax highlighting to help illuminate
structure and mistakes}</li>

<li>
"yank"&nbsp;and "put" similar lines to save editing work {<b>yy</b> and
<b>p</b> commands}</li>
</blockquote>

<li>
use two windows (via the <b>screen</b> command).&nbsp; Write from the editor
periodically {"<b>:w</b>"} while compiling&nbsp; and running&nbsp; in the
other window to catch syntax and other errors early.</li>

